<h2>HVAC Systems in Oklahoma</h2>
<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Oklahoma's continental climate demands HVAC systems capable of handling both intense summer heat and occasional winter cold snaps. The state's cooling season typically runs from May through September, with July and August presenting the greatest challenges as temperatures frequently exceed 95¬∞F with high humidity levels. During these peak months, air conditioning systems may run 12-16 hours daily, making energy efficiency crucial for controlling utility costs. The heating season, while shorter and less intense, still requires reliable systems capable of handling temperatures that can drop below 20¬∞F during winter storms.</p>

<p>For Oklahoma homes, HVAC professionals typically recommend systems with SEER (Seasonal Energy Efficiency Ratio) ratings of 16-18 for optimal balance between efficiency and cost-effectiveness. Higher SEER units, while more expensive upfront, can provide substantial savings during Oklahoma's long, hot summers. Heat pump systems are particularly well-suited to Oklahoma's climate, as they can efficiently provide both heating and cooling. Dual-fuel systems, combining heat pumps with gas furnaces, offer excellent performance and efficiency by automatically switching between electric and gas based on outdoor temperatures and utility rates.</p>

