<h2>Oklahoma Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Oklahoma homeowners have access to several valuable incentives that can significantly reduce the cost of solar and HVAC installations. The cornerstone of solar incentives is the federal Investment Tax Credit (ITC), which allows homeowners to claim 30% of their solar system costs as a direct credit against their federal income taxes. This credit applies to all system components including panels, inverters, mounting equipment, and installation labor. The 30% rate is available through 2032, after which it steps down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034 before expiring for residential installations.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal Solar Investment Tax Credit:</strong> The 30% federal tax credit can be claimed for solar installations completed through 2032. This credit has no cap and can be carried forward to future tax years if it exceeds current tax liability. The credit applies to all qualifying solar equipment and installation costs, potentially saving Oklahoma homeowners \$3,000-8,000 or more depending on system size.</li>
<li><strong>Oklahoma Sales Tax Exemption:</strong> Oklahoma provides a complete exemption from state sales tax on solar energy equipment, including panels, inverters, batteries, and installation materials. This exemption can save homeowners an additional 4.5% on equipment costs, representing savings of \$500-1,500 on typical residential installations.</li>
<li><strong>OG&E Solar Rebate Programs:</strong> Oklahoma Gas & Electric offers various rebate programs for energy-efficient equipment and renewable energy systems. Their residential solar rebate program provides up to \$1,000 for qualified solar installations, subject to program availability and funding. OG&E also offers net metering, allowing customers to receive credit for excess electricity fed back into the grid.</li>
<li><strong>HVAC Efficiency Rebates:</strong> Many Oklahoma utilities, including OG&E, offer rebates for high-efficiency HVAC equipment. These rebates typically range from \$300-800 for qualifying heat pumps and air conditioning systems with SEER ratings of 16 or higher. Some programs also provide additional incentives for smart thermostats and duct sealing services.</li>
<li><strong>Property Tax Considerations:</strong> While Oklahoma doesn't offer specific property tax exemptions for solar installations, the increase in property value from solar systems is generally modest compared to the energy savings generated, making the investment attractive from a tax perspective.</li>
</ul>

